CRITICAL SAFETY WARNING — PLEASE READ BEFORE USE

This skill gives an AI agent (Claude or any skill-aware assistant) the
ability to read, write, rename, and delete files in your Obsidian vault
on macOS. Operations run directly against the vault filesystem with full
read/write privileges. There is NO sandboxing and NO per-call
confirmation — the only safeguards are instructions in the skill telling
the agent to surface destructive changes before performing them, which
is enforcement by convention, not by mechanism.

Potential consequences of misuse include but are not limited to:
- Permanent deletion of notes (after trash-empty or hard delete)
- Overwriting note contents via the replace operation
- Mass-rewriting of links across many files via the rename operation
- Silent or bulk modification of frontmatter, sections, or attachments
- Corruption of structured notes if heading/anchor matching goes wrong
- Loss of in-progress writing not yet captured by Obsidian Sync history

Risks specific to AI-driven use:
- An agent may misinterpret a request and run a destructive query
- A prompt-injection payload reaching the agent (via note contents,
  meeting transcripts, pasted material, or external context) could
  direct it to overwrite, rename, or delete unrelated notes
- A hallucinated path or heading anchor may produce unintended writes
- A buggy regex in a future skill update could mass-rewrite links
  incorrectly across the vault

Recovery expectations:
- If Obsidian Sync is enabled, per-file version history is the primary
  recovery backstop — but retention is finite, and silent drift may go
  unnoticed past the retention window.
- Without Sync, recovery depends entirely on whatever else is running
  (Time Machine, iCloud Drive history, git, Dropbox versions). The
  skill itself maintains no backups.

